hondo717: First let us discuss barb's opener. In modern bridge, most everyone will open her hand. However, there is a question as to whether clubs or spades are better. I mean whether to open 1@C or 1@S. So, let me talk about 5/5 hands with clubs and spades in general. There is some controversy as to whether to open them 1@C or 1@S. It used to be you always opened them 1@C, because it kept the bidding lower, as you could bid 1@S followed by 2@S. If you opened 1@S, you would have to bid 2@C followed by 3@C, which makes the bidding higher. |
PG| ***** 98 ***** |


NT|
However, modern theory says you can open 5/5 hands with clubs and spades, 1@S because it is important to get your 5 spades across ASAP, with all the preempting and bidding that now occurs. Therefore, in general, I think with 5/5 hands in the blacks, 1@S is acceptable, and I have a slight preference for it. On the other hand, with barb's hand, since her spades are not good, and her clubs are, I would have opened 1@C. To recap, in general I prefer 1@S with 5/5 hands, but only slightly, and will sometimes bid 1@C if the clubs are really good and spades not so good. |
PG| ***** 99 ***** |


NT|
Some people are concerned that you would have to reverse to show spades. That is not really true. There is much confusion about reverses anyhow. A reverse is defined as going past your suit at the 2 level to bid a new suit. So, if barb had by-passed 2@C intentionally to bid 2@S, that indeed would be a reverse. But, if the auction was already past 2@C, her 2@S bidding is not a reverse, as 2@C was not available.  The idea is reverses take up extra bidding room, but if you have already bypassed yours suit at the 2 level, the extra bidding room is gone anyway.|
